{"title_page": "Florida Atlantic Owls football", "text_new": "{{short description|Football team of Florida Atlantic University}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName         = Florida Atlantic Owls football\n| CurrentSeason    = 2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team\n| Image            = Florida Atlantic Athletics wordmark.svg\n| ImageSize        = 200\n| FirstYear        = {{start date|2001}}\n| LastYear         =\n| AthleticDirector = Brian White\n| HeadCoach        = [[Willie Taggart]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 1st\n| HCWins           = 0\n| HCLosses         = 0\n| Stadium          = [[FAU Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity     = 29,571\n| FieldName        = \n| StadiumBuilt     = 2011\n| StadSurface      = Natural Turf\n| Location         = [[Boca Raton, Florida]]\n| NCAAdivision     = I FBS\n| Conference       = [[Conference USA]]\n| ConfDivision     = East\n| PastAffiliations = [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]]\n| ATWins           = 103 <!-- As of games through 12/21/19 -->\n| ATLosses         = 129 <!-- As of games through 12/21/19 -->\n| BowlWins         = 4\n| BowlLosses       = 0\n| BowlTies         = \n| PlayoffApps      = \n| Playoffs         = \n| NatlTitles       = \n| NatlFinalist     = \n| ConfTitles       = 3 (2007, 2017, 2019)\n| DivTitles        = 2 (2017, 2019)\n| Rivalries        = [[FIU Panthers football|FIU Panthers]] ([[Shula Bowl|rivalry]])\n| Heismans         = \n| AllAmericans     = 1 \n| uniform          = \n| color1           = \n| color1hex        = \n| color2           = \n| color2hex        = \n| color3           = \n| color3hex        = \n| color4           = \n| color4hex        = \n| FightSong        = FAU Fight Song\n| Mascot           = Owlsley the Owl\n| MarchingBand     = [[Florida Atlantic Marching Owls]]\n| PagFreeLabel     = \n| PagFreeValue     = \n| PagFreeLabel2    = \n| PagFreeValue2    = \n| WebsiteName      = fausports.com\n| WebsiteURL       = https://fausports.com/sports/football\n}}\n'''Florida Atlantic Owls football''' program represents [[Florida Atlantic University]] (FAU) in the sport of [[American football]]. The Owls compete in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the East Division of [[Conference USA]] (CUSA). The Owls' head coach is [[Willie Taggart]], who was previously the head coach of [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State University]]. Florida Atlantic has produced a Sun Belt Conference co-championship team in 2007, two Conference USA championships in 2017 and 2019, along with 3 postseason bowl appearances and one appearance in the [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season#NCAA Division I-AA Playoff bracket|2003 I-AA Playoffs]]. The Owls play their home games at [[FAU Stadium]] which has a [[seating capacity]] of 29,419.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of Florida Atlantic Owls football seasons}}\n\n===Howard Schnellenberger era (2001\u20132011)===\nFlorida Atlantic University football began play in 2001 with legendary coach [[Howard Schnellenberger]] serving as [[head coach]] until 2011. Schnellenberger was a former offensive coordinator with the [[National Football League|NFL]]{{'}}s [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Miami Dolphins]] who, as a head coach, turned around a moribund [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] football program and won a national championship in his fifth season in 1983 after back to back nine win seasons in 1980 and 1981. Schnellenberger also turned around a downtrodden [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] football program, winning the Fiesta Bowl in 1990.\n\n[[File:Howard Schnellenberger Carrfour.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Coach Schnellenberger (blue jacket)]]\nAfter competing their first four years as an [[NCAA Division I-AA|NCAA Division I-AA independent]], the Owls moved to [[Division I-A]] and the [[Sun Belt Conference]]. Starting with [[2010\u201313 Conference USA realignment|the 2013\u201314 school year]], FAU athletics have competed in [[Conference USA]].\n\nIn [[1998 in sports|1998]], Florida Atlantic University announced it was pursuing the creation of an [[NCAA]] [[college football|football]] program and that [[Howard Schnellenberger]] was going to lead the charge, as director of football operations and head coach. After his success in rebuilding programs at Miami and Louisville, Coach Schnellenberger now undertook the role of building a program from scratch. Much like his time at Miami and Louisville, Coach Schnellenberger did not shy from placing lofty expectations and high goals on his newly created program. Even before FAU would play an intercollegiate game, Coach Schnellenberger explained the goal of FAU football would be to play the best teams it can schedule, in order for the program to aim for a national championship in Division I-A football. These extreme goals were not unusual from a man like Coach Schnellenberger.  At Louisville, facing threats from the administration that the football team would be terminated, Schnellenberger made the bold (and now famous) prediction, \"[We are] on a collision course with the national championship.  The only variable is time.\u201d<ref>http://www.msnsportsnet.com/page.cfm?section=6488</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2000, the first practice was held at the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus of FAU, and 164 students showed up to try out for the team.  During the August 29, 2000 first practice, dubbed the inaugural scrimmage game, FAU continued the tradition of Homecoming King, this time including the crowning ceremony of the King as part of the halftime festivities.  The Homecoming King crown was bestowed upon Wayne Burns, having been voted in by the majority of student population from across all the campuses at the time, which totaled five, then running a Q&A gauntlet alongside the top three candidates, conducted by a committee of students and faculty, who then voted to determine if Mr. Burns would move to the winners circle or if the next candidate would get the crown.  Mr. Burns was driven around the scrimmage game field in a convertible Rolls Royce to wave to the 164 students in the stands, many of whom voted for him.  Wayne Burns was and is the oldest Homecoming King to ever receive the honor at FAU. Florida Atlantic joined NCAA Division I-AA, now known as [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I FCS]], as an independent team for the 2001 season.  Its first-ever intercollegiate competition was against [[Slippery Rock University]], which the Owls lost 40\u20137 in front of 25,632 fans at Joe Robbie Stadium, now known as [[Hard Rock Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fausports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/090201aaa.html|title=FAU vs Slippery Rock|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe team finished its inaugural season at 4\u20136 and followed the next season at 2\u20139.  Major accomplishments in its first two seasons include the program's first win, which came in its second game, against [[Bethune\u2013Cookman Wildcats football|Bethune\u2013Cookman]], 31\u201328, and won in the first meeting with newly created [[South Florida]] [[sports rivalry|rival]], [[FIU Panthers football|Florida International University]], 31\u201321.\n\nOn September 15, 2007 FAU defeated its first [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] opponent with a 42\u201339 victory over [[2007 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/ncaa/scoreboards/2007/09/15/35933_viewcast_recap.html |title= FAU vs. Minnesota |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604123525/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/ncaa/scoreboards/2007/09/15/35933_viewcast_recap.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011 }}</ref> Led by [[Rusty Smith (American football)|Rusty Smith]], FAU beat [[2007 Troy Trojans football team|Troy]] in the final game of the 2007 season to become Sun Belt Conference champions and received an invitation to the [[2007 New Orleans Bowl]], its first ever bowl bid. As a result, in just the seventh year of the football program's history, and the third year playing in Division I, Florida Atlantic set an NCAA mark by becoming the second-youngest program ever to receive an invitation to a bowl game.  They were surpassed only by the undefeated [[1958 Air Force Falcons football team|1958 Air Force Falcons]], who had played just one year of Division 1 football before being invited to the [[Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl]], where they played to a scoreless tie against the [[1958 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU Horned Frogs]] on [[1959 Cotton Bowl Classic|January 1, 1959]].\n\nOn August 11, 2011, Howard Schnellenberger announced he would retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/news/2011/8/11/Schnellenberger_to_Retire_as_Football_Coach.aspx|title=Schnellenberger to Retire as Football Coach|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> The Owls ended the 2011 season 1\u201311, with the only victory coming from a 38\u201335 home win over UAB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/sports/football/schedule/2011|title=2011 Football Schedule|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Carl Pelini era (2012\u20132013)===\nOn December 1, 2011 FAU hired [[Carl Pelini]], the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers]] defensive coordinator to become their new head coach, to succeed Schnellenberger.\n\nOn October 30, 2013, Pelini resigned from his position after admitting to school officials he was using illegal drugs, specifically [[marijuana]] and [[cocaine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/fau-now-says-carl-pelini-has-been-fired-with-cause/|title=FAU now says Carl Pelini has been fired with cause|publisher=}}</ref> He, along with defensive coordinator Pete Rekstis, officially stepped down from their positions only three days before the school's homecoming game, which they won 34\u201317 under interim head coach [[Brian Wright (American football)|Brian Wright]].  Under Pelini, the Owls compiled a 5\u201314 record.\n\nWright finished the 2012\u201313 season as the interim head coach, winning the team's last four games and led the Owls to its first bowl-eligible season since 2008\u201309. The Owls finished 6\u20136 for the season but were not invited to a bowl game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/news/2013/12/8/Football_s_2013_Season_Has_Officially_Ended.aspx|title=Football's 2013 Season Has Officially Ended|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> \n\n===Charlie Partridge era (2014\u20132016)===\nOn December 16, 2013, FAU announced it had hired [[Charlie Partridge]] as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/10139059/florida-atlantic-hires-charlie-partridge-arkansas-razorbacks|title=Florida Atlantic hires Partridge of Arkansas|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to accepting the job at FAU, Partridge was the defensive line coach at [[Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121613aaa.html|title=Florida Atlantic University to Introduce New Head Football Coach|publisher=}}</ref>  On November 27, 2016 FAU fired Partridge after 3 consecutive 3\u20139 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/reports-fau-fires-charlie-partridge-as-owls-continue-seeking-relevancy/|title=FAU fires coach Charlie Partridge as Owls continue seeking relevancy|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Lane Kiffin era (2017\u20132019)===\nOn December 12, 2016, it was announced that former [[USC Trojans football|USC]] and [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] head coach [[Lane Kiffin]] would become the Owls' next head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18262108/alabama-crimson-tide-oc-lane-kiffin-next-head-coach-florida-atlantic-owls|title=Alabama OC Lane Kiffin to be next head coach of Florida Atlantic|work=ESPN|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=December 12, 2016|first1=Chris|last1=Low|first2=Brett|last2=McMurphy}}</ref> Kiffin resigned from FAU on December 7, 2019 after a 49\u20136 blowout win against the University of [[2019 UAB Blazers football team|Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB) and before FAU's Boca Raton Bowl appearance against SMU Mustangs to become the head coach at the [[Ole Miss Rebels football|University of Mississippi]] (Ole Miss).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/07/sports/ncaafootball/lane-kiffin-hired-ole-miss.html|title=Lane Kiffin Hired by Ole Miss as Next Coach|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2019-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Kiffin left FAU with a record of 26\u201313 with two first-place finishes in [[Conference USA]]. In December 2019, FAU tight end [[Harrison Bryant]] won the [[John Mackey Award]], becoming the first FAU player to win a major collegiate postseaon award, as well as becoming FAU's first consensus, and later unanimous, [[All-American]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=John |title=FAU\u2019s Harrison Bryant named Mackey Award winner as nation\u2019s best TE |url=https://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/12/11/faus-harrison-bryant-named-mackey-award-winner-as-nations-best-te/ |website=NBC Sports |publisher=NBC Universal |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Bryant Now Officially a Unanimous All-American |url=https://fausports.com/news/2019/12/19/football-bryant-now-officially-a-unanimous-all-american.aspx |website=FAU Sports |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>FAU's first year defensive coordinator, Glenn Spencer, was named the interim head coach to lead the Owls at the Boca Raton Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/sports/20191209/fau-football-owls-players-endorse-interim-coach-glenn-spencer-for-full-time-head-coaching-job|title=FAU football: Owls players endorse interim coach Glenn Spencer for full-time head coaching job|last=Elman|first=Jake|website=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Willie Taggart era (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn December 11, 2019, FAU announced the hiring of [[Willie Taggart]] as the next head coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28276883/willie-taggart-lands-fau-following-fsu-firing|title=FAU turns to Taggart to replace Kiffin as coach|date=2019-12-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Conference affiliations==\n* [[NCAA Division I FCS independent schools|Independent (NCAA Division I-AA)]] (2001\u20132003)\n* [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|Independent (NCAA Division I-A)]] (2004)\n* [[Sun Belt Conference]] (2005\u20132012) \n* [[Conference USA]] (2013\u2013present)\n\n== Championships ==\n=== Conference championships ===\nFlorida Atlantic has won three conference championships, two outright and one shared.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall Record|Conference Record}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2007]]\u2020 || [[Sun Belt Conference]] || [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || 8\u20135 || 6\u20131\n|- \n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || [[Conference USA]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] || 11\u20133 || 8\u20130\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || [[Conference USA]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] / Glenn Spencer <small>(interim)</small>|| 11\u20133* || 7\u20131\n|}\n\u2020 Co-champions  * 2019 Boca Raton Bowl win coached by Glenn Spencer\n\n===Divisional championships===\nAs a member of Conference USA since 2013, Florida Atlantic competes in the East Division. The Owls have won two division titles.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Division|Coach|Opponent|CG result}}\n|-\n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || rowspan=\"2\"|CUSA East || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lane Kiffin]] || [[2017 North Texas Mean Green football team|North Texas]] || '''W''' 41\u201317\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || [[2019 UAB Blazers football team|UAB]] || '''W''' 49\u20136\n|}\n\n==Bowl games==\nFlorida Atlantic has played in 4 bowl games, compiling a record of 4\u20130.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Coach|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2007]] || [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || [[2007 New Orleans Bowl|New Orleans Bowl]] || [[2007 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]] ||'''W''' 44\u201327\n|-\n| [[2008 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2008]] || Howard Schnellenberger || [[2008 Motor City Bowl|Motor City Bowl]] || [[2008 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]] ||'''W''' 24\u201321\n|-\n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] || [[2017 Boca Raton Bowl|Boca Raton Bowl]] || [[2017 Akron Zips football team|Akron]] ||'''W''' 50\u20133\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || Glenn Spencer (interim) || [[2019 Boca Raton Bowl|Boca Raton Bowl]] || [[2019 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]] || '''W''' 52\u201328\n|}\n\n==Head coaches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Coach|Tenure|Seasons|Record|Winning %}}\n|-\n| [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || 2001\u20132011 || 11 || 58\u201374 || {{winpct|58|74}}\n|-\n| [[Carl Pelini]] || 2012\u20132013 || 2 || 5\u201315 || {{winpct|5|15}}\n|-\n|[[Brian Wright (American football)|Brian Wright]] <small>(interim)</small>|| 2013 || 1 || 4\u20130 || {{winpct|4|0}}\n|-\n| [[Charlie Partridge]] || 2014\u20132016 || 3 || 9\u201327 || {{winpct|9|27}}\n|-\n| [[Lane Kiffin]] || 2017\u20132019 || 3 || 26\u201313 || {{winpct|26|13}}\n|-\n| Glenn Spencer <small>(interim)</small> || 2019 || 1 || 1\u20130 || {{winpct|1|0}}\n|-\n| [[Willie Taggart]] || 2020\u2013present || 0 || 0\u20130 || {{winpct|0|0}}\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Florida International===\n{{main article|Shula Bowl}}\n\nThe Shula Bowl is the rivalry game with [[FIU Panthers football|Florida International]]. It was first played in 2002 and has been played every year since then. The winner receives the Don Shula Award.  The game and trophy are named after former Miami Dolphins head coach [[Don Shula]]. The game is typically either in Boca Raton or Miami, though there have been meetings in other locations in the Miami metropolitan area.\n\nIn total the two squads have met 17 times with Florida Atlantic holding a 13\u20134 lead as of the 2019 season conclusion.  The 2005 game does not count with FIU having to vacate their victory due to NCAA violations and penalties.\n\n==Future non-conference opponents==\nAnnounced schedules as of September 18, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Atlantic Owls Future Football Schedules|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/florida-atlantic/|publisher=FBSchedules.com|accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026}}\n|-\n| at [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]]\n| at [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n| at [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| \n| \n| at [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n|- \n| [[Stony Brook Seawolves football|Stony Brook]]\n| at [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force]]\n| at [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]]\n| at [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| at [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]]\n| [[Fordham Rams football|Fordham]]\n| \n| at [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Individual National Award Winners==\n{|cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"font-size:.9em\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|John Mackey Award<br/>{{small|''Best Tight End''}}}}\n|-\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| '''2019''' \u2013 [[Harrison Bryant]]\n\n===Consensus/Unanimous All-Americans===\n10 Florida Atlantic players have been awarded as All-Americans, with one Florida Atlantic player being awarded as a consensus All-American, later becoming a unanimous All-American.\n\n{|cellpadding=\"1\" style=\"width:50%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Florida Atlantic Owls}}; text-align:center;\"| '''Consensus All-Americans'''\n|-\n{{CollegeSecondaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Year(s)|Name|Number|Position}}\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 2019 || [[Harrison Bryant]] || 40 || TE\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Florida Atlantic Owls football navbox}}\n{{Florida Atlantic University}}\n{{Conference USA football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Florida Atlantic Owls Football}}\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic Owls football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Football team of Florida Atlantic University}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName         = Florida Atlantic Owls football\n| CurrentSeason    = 2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team\n| Image            = Florida Atlantic Athletics wordmark.svg\n| ImageSize        = 200\n| FirstYear        = {{start date|2001}}\n| LastYear         =\n| AthleticDirector = Brian White\n| HeadCoach        = [[Willie Taggart]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 1st\n| HCWins           = 0\n| HCLosses         = 0\n| Stadium          = [[FAU Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity     = 29,571\n| FieldName        = \n| StadiumBuilt     = 2011\n| StadSurface      = Natural Turf\n| Location         = [[Boca Raton, Florida]]\n| NCAAdivision     = I FBS\n| Conference       = [[Conference USA]]\n| ConfDivision     = East\n| PastAffiliations = [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]]\n| ATWins           = 103 <!-- As of games through 12/21/19 -->\n| ATLosses         = 129 <!-- As of games through 12/21/19 -->\n| BowlWins         = 4\n| BowlLosses       = 0\n| BowlTies         = \n| PlayoffApps      = \n| Playoffs         = \n| NatlTitles       = \n| NatlFinalist     = \n| ConfTitles       = 3 (2007, 2017, 2019)\n| DivTitles        = 2 (2017, 2019)\n| Rivalries        = [[FIU Panthers football|FIU Panthers]] ([[Shula Bowl|rivalry]])\n| Heismans         = \n| AllAmericans     = 1 \n| uniform          = \n| color1           = \n| color1hex        = \n| color2           = \n| color2hex        = \n| color3           = \n| color3hex        = \n| color4           = \n| color4hex        = \n| FightSong        = FAU Fight Song\n| Mascot           = Owlsley the Owl\n| MarchingBand     = [[Florida Atlantic Marching Owls]]\n| PagFreeLabel     = \n| PagFreeValue     = \n| PagFreeLabel2    = \n| PagFreeValue2    = \n| WebsiteName      = fausports.com\n| WebsiteURL       = https://fausports.com/sports/football\n}}\n'''Florida Atlantic Owls football''' program represents [[Florida Atlantic University]] (FAU) in the sport of [[American football]]. The Owls compete in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the East Division of [[Conference USA]] (CUSA). The Owls' head coach is [[Willie Taggart]], who was previously the head coach of [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State University]]. Florida Atlantic has produced a Sun Belt Conference co-championship team in 2007, two Conference USA championships in 2017 and 2019, along with 3 postseason bowl appearances and one appearance in the [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season#NCAA Division I-AA Playoff bracket|2003 I-AA Playoffs]]. The Owls play their home games at [[FAU Stadium]] which has a [[seating capacity]] of 29,419.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of Florida Atlantic Owls football seasons}}\n\n===Howard Schnellenberger era (2001\u20132011)===\nFlorida Atlantic University football began play in 2001 with legendary coach [[Howard Schnellenberger]] serving as [[head coach]] until 2011. Schnellenberger was a former offensive coordinator with the [[National Football League|NFL]]{{'}}s [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Miami Dolphins]] who, as a head coach, turned around a moribund [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] football program and won a national championship in his fifth season in 1983 after back to back nine win seasons in 1980 and 1981. Schnellenberger also turned around a downtrodden [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] football program, winning the Fiesta Bowl in 1990.\n\n[[File:Howard Schnellenberger Carrfour.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Coach Schnellenberger (blue jacket)]]\nAfter competing their first four years as an [[NCAA Division I-AA|NCAA Division I-AA independent]], the Owls moved to [[Division I-A]] and the [[Sun Belt Conference]]. Starting with [[2010\u201313 Conference USA realignment|the 2013\u201314 school year]], FAU athletics have competed in [[Conference USA]].\n\nIn [[1998 in sports|1998]], Florida Atlantic University announced it was pursuing the creation of an [[NCAA]] [[college football|football]] program and that [[Howard Schnellenberger]] was going to lead the charge, as director of football operations and head coach. After his success in rebuilding programs at Miami and Louisville, Coach Schnellenberger now undertook the role of building a program from scratch. Much like his time at Miami and Louisville, Coach Schnellenberger did not shy from placing lofty expectations and high goals on his newly created program. Even before FAU would play an intercollegiate game, Coach Schnellenberger explained the goal of FAU football would be to play the best teams it can schedule, in order for the program to aim for a national championship in Division I-A football. These extreme goals were not unusual from a man like Coach Schnellenberger.  At Louisville, facing threats from the administration that the football team would be terminated, Schnellenberger made the bold (and now famous) prediction, \"[We are] on a collision course with the national championship.  The only variable is time.\u201d<ref>http://www.msnsportsnet.com/page.cfm?section=6488</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2000, the first practice was held at the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus of FAU, and 164 students showed up to try out for the team.  During the August 29, 2000 first practice, dubbed the inaugural scrimmage game, FAU continued the tradition of Homecoming King, this time including the crowning ceremony of the King as part of the halftime festivities.  The Homecoming King crown was bestowed upon Wayne Burns, having been voted in by the majority of student population from across all the campuses at the time, which totaled five, then running a Q&A gauntlet alongside the top three candidates, conducted by a committee of students and faculty, who then voted to determine if Mr. Burns would move to the winners circle or if the next candidate would get the crown.  Mr. Burns was driven around the scrimmage game field in a convertible Rolls Royce to wave to the 164 students in the stands, many of whom voted for him.  Wayne Burns was and is the oldest Homecoming King to ever receive the honor at FAU. Florida Atlantic joined NCAA Division I-AA, now known as [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I FCS]], as an independent team for the 2001 season.  Its first-ever intercollegiate competition was against [[Slippery Rock University]], which the Owls lost 40\u20137 in front of 25,632 fans at Joe Robbie Stadium, now known as [[Hard Rock Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fausports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/090201aaa.html|title=FAU vs Slippery Rock|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe team finished its inaugural season at 4\u20136 and followed the next season at 2\u20139.  Major accomplishments in its first two seasons include the program's first win, which came in its second game, against [[Bethune\u2013Cookman Wildcats football|Bethune\u2013Cookman]], 31\u201328, and won in the first meeting with newly created [[South Florida]] [[sports rivalry|rival]], [[FIU Panthers football|Florida International University]], 31\u201321.\n\nOn September 15, 2007 FAU defeated its first [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] opponent with a 42\u201339 victory over [[2007 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/ncaa/scoreboards/2007/09/15/35933_viewcast_recap.html |title= FAU vs. Minnesota |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604123525/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/ncaa/scoreboards/2007/09/15/35933_viewcast_recap.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011 }}</ref> Led by [[Rusty Smith (American football)|Rusty Smith]], FAU beat [[2007 Troy Trojans football team|Troy]] in the final game of the 2007 season to become Sun Belt Conference champions and received an invitation to the [[2007 New Orleans Bowl]], its first ever bowl bid. As a result, in just the seventh year of the football program's history, and the third year playing in Division I, Florida Atlantic set an NCAA mark by becoming the second-youngest program ever to receive an invitation to a bowl game.  They were surpassed only by the undefeated [[1958 Air Force Falcons football team|1958 Air Force Falcons]], who had played just one year of Division 1 football before being invited to the [[Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl]], where they played to a scoreless tie against the [[1958 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU Horned Frogs]] on [[1959 Cotton Bowl Classic|January 1, 1959]].\n\nOn August 11, 2011, Howard Schnellenberger announced he would retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/news/2011/8/11/Schnellenberger_to_Retire_as_Football_Coach.aspx|title=Schnellenberger to Retire as Football Coach|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> The Owls ended the 2011 season 1\u201311, with the only victory coming from a 38\u201335 home win over UAB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/sports/football/schedule/2011|title=2011 Football Schedule|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Carl Pelini era (2012\u20132013)===\nOn December 1, 2011 FAU hired [[Carl Pelini]], the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers]] defensive coordinator to become their new head coach, to succeed Schnellenberger.\n\nOn October 30, 2013, Pelini resigned from his position after admitting to school officials he was using illegal drugs, specifically [[marijuana]] and [[cocaine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/fau-now-says-carl-pelini-has-been-fired-with-cause/|title=FAU now says Carl Pelini has been fired with cause|publisher=}}</ref> He, along with defensive coordinator Pete Rekstis, officially stepped down from their positions only three days before the school's homecoming game, which they won 34\u201317 under interim head coach [[Brian Wright (American football)|Brian Wright]].  Under Pelini, the Owls compiled a 5\u201314 record.\n\nWright finished the 2012\u201313 season as the interim head coach, winning the team's last four games and led the Owls to its first bowl-eligible season since 2008\u201309. The Owls finished 6\u20136 for the season but were not invited to a bowl game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fausports.com/news/2013/12/8/Football_s_2013_Season_Has_Officially_Ended.aspx|title=Football's 2013 Season Has Officially Ended|website=Florida Atlantic University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> \n\n===Charlie Partridge era (2014\u20132016)===\nOn December 16, 2013, FAU announced it had hired [[Charlie Partridge]] as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/10139059/florida-atlantic-hires-charlie-partridge-arkansas-razorbacks|title=Florida Atlantic hires Partridge of Arkansas|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to accepting the job at FAU, Partridge was the defensive line coach at [[Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121613aaa.html|title=Florida Atlantic University to Introduce New Head Football Coach|publisher=}}</ref>  On November 27, 2016 FAU fired Partridge after 3 consecutive 3\u20139 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/reports-fau-fires-charlie-partridge-as-owls-continue-seeking-relevancy/|title=FAU fires coach Charlie Partridge as Owls continue seeking relevancy|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Lane Kiffin era (2017\u20132019)===\nOn December 12, 2016, it was announced that former [[USC Trojans football|USC]] and [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] head coach [[Lane Kiffin]] would become the Owls' next head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18262108/alabama-crimson-tide-oc-lane-kiffin-next-head-coach-florida-atlantic-owls|title=Alabama OC Lane Kiffin to be next head coach of Florida Atlantic|work=ESPN|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=December 12, 2016|first1=Chris|last1=Low|first2=Brett|last2=McMurphy}}</ref> Kiffin resigned from FAU on December 7, 2019 after a 49\u20136 blowout win against the University of [[2019 UAB Blazers football team|Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB) and before FAU's Boca Raton Bowl appearance against SMU Mustangs to become the head coach at the [[Ole Miss Rebels football|University of Mississippi]] (Ole Miss).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/07/sports/ncaafootball/lane-kiffin-hired-ole-miss.html|title=Lane Kiffin Hired by Ole Miss as Next Coach|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2019-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Kiffin left FAU with a record of 26\u201313 with two first place finishes in [[Conference USA]]. In December 2019, FAU tight end [[Harrison Bryant]] won the [[John Mackey Award]], becoming the first FAU player to win a major collegiate postseaon award, as well as becoming FAU's first consensus, and later unanimous, [[All-American]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=John |title=FAU\u2019s Harrison Bryant named Mackey Award winner as nation\u2019s best TE |url=https://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/12/11/faus-harrison-bryant-named-mackey-award-winner-as-nations-best-te/ |website=NBC Sports |publisher=NBC Universal |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Bryant Now Officially a Unanimous All-American |url=https://fausports.com/news/2019/12/19/football-bryant-now-officially-a-unanimous-all-american.aspx |website=FAU Sports |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>FAU's first year defensive coordinator, Glenn Spencer, was named the interim head coach to lead the Owls at the Boca Raton Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/sports/20191209/fau-football-owls-players-endorse-interim-coach-glenn-spencer-for-full-time-head-coaching-job|title=FAU football: Owls players endorse interim coach Glenn Spencer for full-time head coaching job|last=Elman|first=Jake|website=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Willie Taggart era (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn December 11, 2019, FAU announced the hiring of [[Willie Taggart]] as the next head coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28276883/willie-taggart-lands-fau-following-fsu-firing|title=FAU turns to Taggart to replace Kiffin as coach|date=2019-12-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Conference affiliations==\n* [[NCAA Division I FCS independent schools|Independent (NCAA Division I-AA)]] (2001\u20132003)\n* [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|Independent (NCAA Division I-A)]] (2004)\n* [[Sun Belt Conference]] (2005\u20132012) \n* [[Conference USA]] (2013\u2013present)\n\n== Championships ==\n=== Conference championships ===\nFlorida Atlantic has won three conference championships, two outright and one shared.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall Record|Conference Record}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2007]]\u2020 || [[Sun Belt Conference]] || [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || 8\u20135 || 6\u20131\n|- \n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || [[Conference USA]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] || 11\u20133 || 8\u20130\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || [[Conference USA]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] / Glenn Spencer <small>(interim)</small>|| 11\u20133* || 7\u20131\n|}\n\u2020 Co-champions  * 2019 Boca Raton Bowl win coached by Glenn Spencer\n\n===Divisional championships===\nAs a member of Conference USA since 2013, Florida Atlantic competes in the East Division. The Owls have won two division titles.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Division|Coach|Opponent|CG result}}\n|-\n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || rowspan=\"2\"|CUSA East || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lane Kiffin]] || [[2017 North Texas Mean Green football team|North Texas]] || '''W''' 41\u201317\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || [[2019 UAB Blazers football team|UAB]] || '''W''' 49\u20136\n|}\n\n==Bowl games==\nFlorida Atlantic has played in 4 bowl games, compiling a record of 4\u20130.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Season|Coach|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2007]] || [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || [[2007 New Orleans Bowl|New Orleans Bowl]] || [[2007 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]] ||'''W''' 44\u201327\n|-\n| [[2008 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2008]] || Howard Schnellenberger || [[2008 Motor City Bowl|Motor City Bowl]] || [[2008 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]] ||'''W''' 24\u201321\n|-\n| [[2017 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2017]] || [[Lane Kiffin]] || [[2017 Boca Raton Bowl|Boca Raton Bowl]] || [[2017 Akron Zips football team|Akron]] ||'''W''' 50\u20133\n|-\n| [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|2019]] || Glenn Spencer (interim) || [[2019 Boca Raton Bowl|Boca Raton Bowl]] || [[2019 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]] || '''W''' 52\u201328\n|}\n\n==Head coaches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Coach|Tenure|Seasons|Record|Winning %}}\n|-\n| [[Howard Schnellenberger]] || 2001\u20132011 || 11 || 58\u201374 || {{winpct|58|74}}\n|-\n| [[Carl Pelini]] || 2012\u20132013 || 2 || 5\u201315 || {{winpct|5|15}}\n|-\n|[[Brian Wright (American football)|Brian Wright]] <small>(interim)</small>|| 2013 || 1 || 4\u20130 || {{winpct|4|0}}\n|-\n| [[Charlie Partridge]] || 2014\u20132016 || 3 || 9\u201327 || {{winpct|9|27}}\n|-\n| [[Lane Kiffin]] || 2017\u20132019 || 3 || 26\u201313 || {{winpct|26|13}}\n|-\n| Glenn Spencer <small>(interim)</small> || 2019 || 1 || 1\u20130 || {{winpct|1|0}}\n|-\n| [[Willie Taggart]] || 2020\u2013present || 0 || 0\u20130 || {{winpct|0|0}}\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Florida International===\n{{main article|Shula Bowl}}\n\nThe Shula Bowl is the rivalry game with [[FIU Panthers football|Florida International]]. It was first played in 2002 and has been played every year since then. The winner receives the Don Shula Award.  The game and trophy are named after former Miami Dolphins head coach [[Don Shula]]. The game is typically either in Boca Raton or Miami, though there have been meetings in other locations in the Miami metropolitan area.\n\nIn total the two squads have met 17 times with Florida Atlantic holding a 13\u20134 lead as of the 2019 season conclusion.  The 2005 game does not count with FIU having to vacate their victory due to NCAA violations and penalties.\n\n==Future non-conference opponents==\nAnnounced schedules as of September 18, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Atlantic Owls Future Football Schedules|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/florida-atlantic/|publisher=FBSchedules.com|accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026}}\n|-\n| at [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]]\n| at [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n| at [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| \n| \n| at [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n|- \n| [[Stony Brook Seawolves football|Stony Brook]]\n| at [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force]]\n| at [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]]\n| at [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| at [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]]\n| [[Fordham Rams football|Fordham]]\n| \n| at [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Individual National Award Winners==\n{|cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"font-size:.9em\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|John Mackey Award<br/>{{small|''Best Tight End''}}}}\n|-\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| '''2019''' \u2013 [[Harrison Bryant]]\n\n===Consensus/Unanimous All-Americans===\n10 Florida Atlantic players have been awarded as All-Americans, with one Florida Atlantic player being awarded as a consensus All-American, later becoming an unanimous All-American.\n\n{|cellpadding=\"1\" style=\"width:50%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Florida Atlantic Owls}}; text-align:center;\"| '''Consensus All-Americans'''\n|-\n{{CollegeSecondaryHeader|team=Florida Atlantic Owls|Year(s)|Name|Number|Position}}\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 2019 || [[Harrison Bryant]] || 40 || TE\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{